The error [dotLottie-common]: no animation selected typically occurs because the .lottie file (which is actually a compressed .zip package) contains multiple animations, but your player doesn't know which one to play first. 
1. Immediate Fix: Specify the "activeAnimationId"
A .lottie file can bundle several animations. If you don't specify an ID, the player may fail to default to the first one. 
Web (React/Vue/JS): Add the activeAnimationId property to your component.
javascript
<DotLottieReact
  src="path/to/animation.lottie"
  activeAnimationId="animation_1" // Use the specific ID from your manifest
  autoplay
  loop
/>
Use code with caution.

Flutter: Use the DotLottieLoader and ensure you are selecting a single animation from the bundle.
dart
DotLottieLoader.fromAsset("assets/anim.lottie",
  frameBuilder: (ctx, dotlottie) {
    if (dotlottie != null) {
      // Explicitly select the first animation if the ID is unknown
      return Lottie.memory(dotlottie.animations.values.single); 
    }
    return Container();
  }
);
Use code with caution.


2. Check the File Structure (The "Manifest" Issue)
The error often triggers when the internal manifest.json inside your .lottie file is missing or doesn't list any animations. 
Try this: Rename your .lottie file to .zip and open it. Check if there is a manifest.json file inside.
The Fix: If the file is corrupted or missing a manifest, re-export it from the LottieFiles Converter to ensure a valid structure. 
3. Wait for the Player to be "Ready"
If you are triggering the animation dynamically (via code), the player might try to "select" the animation before the file has fully unzipped in memory. 
The Fix: Wrap your play command in a "ready" event listener.
javascript
dotLottieInstance.addEventListener("ready", () => {
  dotLottieInstance.play();
});
Use code with caution.


4. Verify Remote URL Settings (CORS) 
If you are loading the file from a URL, the player might fail to "see" the animations inside the file if the server blocks access. 
Check: Ensure your server has CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) enabled for .lottie files. 
Which framework (React, Flutter, or Swift) are you using for this animation? I can give you the exact code to target the activeAnimationId

